<p>signErrorAns = $signErrorAns</p> -->
<!--testing-->

  
<p>Factor 
  <me>$factoredExpr{expand}</me>
</p>
  <p><m>$factoredExpr{expand} = </m>
       
    <answer name="ans11" >
      <mathInput name="userFraction"/>
      <award symbolicEquality="true" simplifyOnCompare>
      <when>
        <hasSameFactoring>$userFraction $factoredExpr
        </hasSameFactoring>
      </when>
      </award>
      <award name="noFactoring" credit="0">$factoredExpr{expand}</award>
      <award name="signError" credit="0">$signErrorAns</award>
  </answer></p>

  <feedback condition="$noFactoring">
  <p>To factor the quadratic expression <m>($factoredExpr{expand})</m>, means to split into two factors, if possible. Generally, this means to separate it into two binomial terms, or a monomial term and a binomial term. Here are two simple examples:</p>
<ul>
  <li><m>x^2 + 4x - 5 = (x - 1)(x + 5)</m></li>
  <li><m>2x^2 + 4x = 2x(x + 2)</m></li>
</ul>
  
<p><em>How to check</em>: It is ok to use a bit of trial and error when factoring. Choose a possible factoring, and then FOIL it out to see if it matches your original, expanded quadratic expression.</p>
  </feedback>

  <feedback condition="$signError">
    <p>It looks like you have a sign error somewhere.</p>
  <p><em>How to check</em>: FOIL out your factored answer to see if it matches your original, expanded quadratic expression.</p></feedback>
    

