<hint name="helpSection"><title>Worked Example</title>
    <p>First, check to see if the expression has a greatest common factor. In this case, we do not have a GCF, so we proceed to factor the trinomial.</p>
<p>For a trinomial with an <m>x^2</m> coefficient of <m>1</m>, it is sufficient to ask "what two factors of the constant term add up to the coefficient on the <m>x</m> term?"" Here is a simple worked example:</p>
        <me>\text{Factor}\;\;x^2 + 5x - 50</me>
  We need two factors of <m>-50</m> that add up to <m>5</m>. The factor pairs of <m>-50</m> are
    <md>
      <mrow>(1\;\; \amp\text{and}\;\; -50)\;\;\text{or}\;\;(-1\;\; \text{and}\;\; 50)</mrow>
      <mrow>(2\;\; \amp\text{and}\;\; -25)\;\;\text{or}\;\;(-2\;\; \text{and}\;\; 25)</mrow>
      <mrow>(5\;\; \amp\text{and}\;\; -10)\;\;\text{or}\;\;(-5\;\; \text{and}\;\; 10)</mrow>
      </md> 
  The factor pair that adds up to <m>5</m> is <m>(10</m> and <m>-5)</m>. Therefore, we have
  <me>x^2 + 5x - 50 = (x + 10)(x - 5)</me>
<p><em>How to check</em>: Always FOIL it out to see if it matches your original expression.</p>
    <ref uri="https://www.youtube.com/embed/3yXEyF_5yF0?feature=oembed&rel=0&rel=0" createButton>Textbook link</ref>
    <video name="BA-basics_p15ExVideo"/>
  </hint>


<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->
  
<solution>
<p>First, check to see if the expression has a greatest common divisor. In this case, the greatest common divisor is <m>1</m>, so we can proceed with factoring the quadratic as it is.</p>
<p>In this exercise, since the coefficient on the <m>x^2</m> term is <m>1</m>, we can either use the box method, or ask what factors of <m>-$d</m> will add up to <m>$c</m>? The two factors are <m>$a</m> and <m>-$b</m>: 
  <me>$factoredExpr{expand} = $factoredExpr{simplify}.</me>
</p>
</solution>
</problem>
